"""
MKT Context Commentary — John chapters 17–18
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-john-17-18.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/john.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/john.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/john.json (prior chapters 1–11 for continuity)
- data/commentary/ellicott/john.json (philological and historical background)
- data/parallels/john.json (synoptic parallels for ch.18)

Key decisions in this range:
- "The Evangelist" throughout (following established pattern from prior scripts)
- Chapter 17 treated as a single liturgical act: the High Priestly Prayer (a title
  attested from David Chytraeus, 1561; not an ancient label, but the structural
  reading of vv.17–19 as priestly consecration is textually grounded)
- Annas/Caiaphas distinction: Annas is treated as the de facto power despite the
  formal title belonging to Caiaphas; historical background from Josephus used
- The "charcoal fire" (anthrakia) at 18:18 is noted as a deliberate echo of 21:9;
  this connection is Evangelistic, not merely incidental — the John 21 scene
  is a deliberate restoration scene built on the same vocabulary
- Pilate's juridical procedure: Roman accusatio process noted at 18:29–32;
  the ius gladii note at 18:31 grounded in Josephus and Talmudic evidence
- The Barabbas custom (18:38–40): noted as attested only in the Gospels; its
  historical status is uncertain but the narrative logic is clear
- Honor-shame and patron-client frameworks maintained from prior scripts
- "The Jewish leaders" / "the high-priestly party" used for hoi Ioudaioi in
  official/political contexts (following prior script convention)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


JOHN = {
  "17": {
    "1": '<p>The prayer of chapter 17 is often called the High Priestly Prayer — a name coined by the Lutheran theologian David Chytraeus in 1561, based on the priestly consecration language of verses 17–19. The chapter concludes the farewell discourse that began at the supper table (ch. 13), and it is spoken in the disciples\' hearing, making it simultaneously an act of prayer and an act of instruction: the disciples overhear the Son speaking to the Father about them. The upward look toward heaven in prayer was standard Jewish posture — it expressed orientation toward God\'s dwelling place and signaled the transition from address to God\'s people to address to God himself.</p><p>The word "hour" (<em>hōra</em>) has carried theological weight throughout this Gospel (2:4; 7:30; 8:20; 12:23, 27; 13:1). Here its arrival is stated without qualification. The prayer presupposes what the Passover setting makes explicit: the hour of sacrifice has come, and Jesus approaches it in conscious, willing readiness rather than as a victim overtaken by events.</p>',

    "2": '<p>The phrasing "authority over all flesh" is a Semitic idiom (כָּל-בָּשָׂר / <em>pāsas sarx</em>) meaning all humanity — the full scope of created human beings. Jewish legal tradition had a precise concept of authorized agency (<em>shaliach</em>): the one sent by another acts with the full authority of the sender and is treated as the sender himself. Jesus\'s authority over humanity is here framed as a delegated commission — not independently seized power, but authority granted by the Father for a specific purpose. The purpose clause that follows (granting eternal life) defines what that authority is for.</p>',

    "3": '<p>The definition of eternal life as <em>knowing</em> God echoes the covenantal knowledge language of the Hebrew Scriptures, where "knowing" Yahweh meant entering into and living within the covenant relationship — not merely intellectual acknowledgment (Jer 31:34; Hos 6:6; Exod 33:13). This is the knowing of the covenant partner, not the detached knowledge of an observer. The phrase "the only true God" asserts monotheism in a context where Roman religion was thoroughly polytheist and "gods many and lords many" (1 Cor 8:5) were the cultural norm. The appositive "Jesus Christ, whom you have sent" is unusual — this is the only place in the Gospel where Jesus refers to himself in the third person by his full name in prayer, suggesting a formal, almost creedal register.</p>',

    "4": '<p>The verb "finished" (<em>eteleiósa</em>) anticipates the cry "It is finished" (<em>tetelestai</em>) from the cross (19:30). Both are forms of the same root, <em>teleō</em>. In the priestly context the word is significant: Levitical texts repeatedly describe the completion of temple service and the consecration of priests as "filling the hand" or completing (<em>millē\' yad</em> in Hebrew). Jesus frames his entire earthly ministry as a priestly service rendered to the Father — not a task interrupted by death, but a work brought to completion through it.</p>',

    "5": '<p>The petition for restoration of pre-incarnate glory grounds the prayer in eternity rather than history: what Jesus asks for is not something new but the recovery of what was laid aside at the Incarnation. The phrase "before the world existed" directly echoes the Prologue (1:1–2) and aligns with Second Temple Jewish traditions that described pre-existent Wisdom present with God before creation (Prov 8:22–31; Sir 24:3–9). The audience familiar with these traditions would have recognized the claim as a statement about a figure who occupied the divine side of the Creator–creation distinction.</p>',

    "6": '<p>In Jewish thought, God\'s "name" was far more than a label. The Tetragrammaton (יהוה) was the name above all names, never pronounced in Second Temple Judaism — it was circumlocuted as <em>Adonai</em> (Lord) or <em>HaShem</em> (the Name). To "know the name" of God meant to have access to his character, to stand in relationship with him, to have been admitted to covenant. Jesus\'s claim to have "revealed your name" to the disciples is a claim to have disclosed the full character of the Father — the same claim the Prologue makes when it says the Son has "made him known" (1:18, using <em>exēgēsato</em>, the same word used for authoritative interpretation). The disciples are described as those the Father "gave" Jesus "out of the world" — a Johannine election idiom that appears repeatedly in chapters 6 and 17.</p>',

    "7": '<p>The logic of verse 7 traces a chain of revelation: everything given to Jesus comes from the Father; the disciples now know this to be the case. In rabbinic tradition the chain of authoritative transmission was foundational to the legitimacy of teaching: a claim to teach Torah required tracing the tradition back through recognized authorities. Here the chain runs Father → Son → disciples, and the disciples\' recognition of this chain is presented as the mark of their belonging to the circle of genuine revelation.</p>',

    "8": '<p>The distinction between "giving the words" and "they accepted them" maps onto the honor-shame structure of ancient instruction: a teacher\'s words were a gift that placed the recipient in a position of obligation. Acceptance of the teacher\'s words was not merely cognitive agreement but a relational act — acknowledging the authority of the one who spoke. The disciples\' belief that the Father "sent" Jesus uses the <em>shaliach</em> concept again: the sender is fully present in and through the one sent, so recognizing the sent one is recognizing the sender.</p>',

    "9": '<p>The prayer\'s explicit limitation ("I am not praying for the world, but for those you have given me") is not a statement of cosmic indifference but a reflection of priestly intercessory structure. The high priest on the Day of Atonement made atonement specifically for the community of Israel, not for all nations — the scope of the intercession was defined by the covenant community. Jesus\'s prayer here follows this model: he intercedes for those who have been entrusted to him, the nucleus of the new covenant community. The prayer for "the world" in a broader sense comes in verse 21, where the unity of the disciples is itself directed toward the world\'s belief.</p>',

    "10": '<p>The mutual possession of Father and Son ("all I have is yours, and all you have is mine") expresses the covenantal solidarity of the divine relationship using the language of <em>communio bonorum</em> — the total sharing of goods between persons in the most intimate covenant bond. In ancient Mediterranean family structures, a son\'s assets were in principle the father\'s and vice versa; the statement intensifies this to absolute mutuality. The claim that glory has come to Jesus "through them" — through the disciples — points toward the community as the site of divine self-disclosure, a theme the Evangelist develops in the unity prayers of verses 20–23.</p>',

    "11": '<p>Jesus addresses the Father here as "Holy Father" — a unique form of address in the New Testament, combining the intimacy of the Abba address with the holiness language of Isaiah\'s throne vision (Isa 6:3). In Second Temple Judaism, God\'s holiness was not merely a moral category but an ontological one: it marked the absolute difference between the divine and the creaturely. Combining this address with "Father" was theologically charged — it said simultaneously that God was radically other and intimately accessible. The protection requested operates through the Father\'s "name" (character and power), not merely external force.</p>',

    "12": '<p>The phrase "the one doomed to destruction" translates a Greek idiom, "the son of perdition" (<em>ho huios tēs apōleias</em>), which uses the Semitic "son of X" construction to denote a person defined by, or destined for, a particular outcome. The same phrase appears in 2 Thessalonians 2:3 for the eschatological adversary figure. Here it characterizes Judas, whose defection is presented not as a failure of Jesus\'s protective mission but as a fulfillment of Scripture (Ps 41:9, cited explicitly in 13:18). The Evangelist consistently frames Judas\'s betrayal within divine foreknowledge: it happened "that Scripture would be fulfilled," not despite it.</p>',

    "13": '<p>"The full measure of my joy" echoes the covenant joy language of the Psalms, where rejoicing in God\'s presence was the mark of those who dwelt in his courts (Ps 16:11; 21:6; 43:4). Speaking this prayer while still in the world — in the hearing of the disciples — serves a pedagogical function: it models for them what the relationship between the Son and the Father looks like, so that they can inhabit the same register of joyful intimacy. The phrase is not incidental sentiment but a description of the inner quality that the Farewell Discourse has been designed to transfer.</p>',

    "14": '<p>The world\'s hatred of the disciples because they are "not of the world" draws on a distinction that runs throughout the Farewell Discourse. In the honor-shame dynamics of the ancient Mediterranean, a person\'s community defined their identity, obligations, and social claims. To be "of the world" meant to be shaped by and oriented toward the dominant value system — what the world honors, fears, and pursues. The disciples have accepted a different set of loyalties, which makes them anomalous within that system and therefore threatening. The hostility is not primarily moral but structural: the world rejects those who no longer play by its rules.</p>',

    "15": '<p>The prayer\'s precision here is notable: the request is not for removal from the world\'s sphere but for protection within it. This directly counters any withdrawal or sectarian reading of the community of disciples: they are not to become a protected enclave removed from contact with the world. The "evil one" (<em>ho ponēros</em>) as a personal figure — an agent of corruption and hostility — parallels the petition in the Lord\'s Prayer (Matt 6:13, "deliver us from the evil one"). The Johannine vision of the disciples in the world but not of it is a mission posture, not a retreat posture.</p>',

    "16": '<p>The repetition of verse 14\'s formula ("they are not of the world, even as I am not of it") creates a structural parallel: the disciples\' posture is modeled on Jesus\'s own. This is not an ontological claim about the disciples\' nature but a relational and missional one — their primary loyalty and orientation has been redirected. In a world where a person\'s community membership defined nearly every social obligation, this reorientation had practical consequences: loyalty to the community of Jesus superseded the demands of ethnic, civic, and familial networks.</p>',

    "17": '<p>"Sanctify them by the truth; your word is truth." The verb <em>hagiazō</em> (sanctify, set apart) had specific priestly connotations in the LXX: the consecration of priests and the dedication of sacred objects to God\'s service. Leviticus 8 describes the seven-day consecration of Aaron and his sons; Exodus 28 specifies the garments and rites by which they were set apart for priestly function. The Deuteronomic tradition also emphasized the Torah as the instrument of covenant formation — the word that shaped the people into God\'s own community. Here the instrument of sanctification is not ritual action but truth — the body of revelation that Jesus has transmitted from the Father.</p>',

    "18": '<p>The sending of the disciples into the world mirrors the language of Jesus\'s own mission: "as you sent me into the world, I have sent them into the world." The pattern is <em>shaliach</em> extended: the sender is present in the sent one; the original sending is replicated and extended through a chain of authorized representatives. This verse is the Johannine equivalent of what the Synoptics call the Great Commission (Matt 28:18–20; Mark 16:15), but it is situated within the intercessory prayer rather than as a post-resurrection command — the mission is part of the prayer\'s logic, not an afterthought.</p>',

    "19": '<p>"For them I sanctify myself" — the verb used here for Jesus\'s self-consecration is the same verb used for the sanctification of the disciples in verse 17 and for priestly consecration throughout the Levitical tradition. A priest did not enter the sanctuary without first purifying and setting himself apart; Jesus presents himself as the priest who consecrates himself before the sacrifice, which is simultaneously the sacrifice itself. The Evangelist\'s priestly register here is deliberate and developed: Jesus is both priest and offering, and his self-consecration serves the sanctification of those he represents before God.</p>',

    "20": '<p>The scope of the prayer expands from the Eleven (or Ten, with Judas now absent) to all future believers — those who will come to faith "through their message." The Greek word for "message" (<em>logos</em>) is the same word used for Jesus\'s own revelation throughout the Gospel, binding the apostolic witness to the original word of the Son. The Evangelist presents the chain of testimony (Father → Son → disciples → future believers) as the means by which the prayer\'s petitions extend across time. This expansion is not incidental: it is the theological grounding for the existence of every subsequent generation of the community.</p>',

    "21": '<p>The unity prayer ("that all of them may be one, Father, just as you are in me and I am in you") uses the divine relationship as the model and source of the community\'s unity. In ancient Mediterranean culture, unity within a group was not primarily an emotional state but a practical reality of shared purpose, resources, and loyalty — the internal coherence that made a community effective. The Evangelist presses beyond social unity to something grounded in the Trinitarian relationship itself. The final clause — "so that the world may believe that you have sent me" — makes the community\'s unity instrumental for mission: it is the evidence that compels the world\'s recognition.</p>',

    "22": '<p>"The glory that you gave me, that they may be one as we are one." The glory (<em>doxa</em>) given to the disciples is not a separate commodity but a participation in the relational reality between Father and Son. In the honor culture of the first century, glory was the public acknowledgment of worth — it had to be recognized and conferred by others. But the glory Jesus speaks of here operates on a different logic: it is given by the Father, passed through the Son, and extended to the community. It creates unity not by increasing individual prestige but by drawing all into the same pattern of mutual indwelling.</p>',

    "23": '<p>The phrase "brought to complete unity" translates a perfect passive participle of <em>teleioō</em> — the same root as "finished" in verse 4 and "It is finished" in 19:30. The completion of Jesus\'s work and the perfected unity of the community are linguistically linked. The purpose of this unity is explicitly stated: "that the world may know that you sent me and have loved them even as you have loved me." The love of the Father for the disciples is said to be identical in quality to the love of the Father for the Son — a claim without parallel in the Jewish tradition of the period, where the distance between divine and human love was normally emphasized.</p>',

    "24": '<p>The desire that the disciples "see my glory" echoes Moses\'s request in Exodus 33:18 ("Show me your glory"), which Yahweh answered by revealing his character rather than his unmediated presence. The Evangelist has structured the Fourth Gospel around a series of progressive revelations of Jesus\'s glory (2:11; 11:4, 40; 12:28; 17:1), each pointing toward the final glorification. The vision the disciples are being promised is not a visual spectacle but the knowledge that the glory given to Jesus before creation was grounded in love — "because you loved me before the foundation of the world," a love that preceded even the created order.</p>',

    "25": '<p>"Righteous Father" is another unique address, pairing the relational term "Father" with the judicial attribute "righteous." The world\'s failure to know the Father sets up the contrast: Jesus knows him, and the disciples have come to know that Jesus was sent — they stand on the side of knowledge, not ignorance. The address "Righteous Father" implies an appeal to divine justice: the prayer\'s petitions are grounded not just in relationship but in the righteousness of the Father who will vindicate what has been revealed and protect those who have received it.</p>',

    "26": '<p>The final verse closes the prayer with a double promise: continued revelation of the Father\'s name (character), and the indwelling of the love with which the Father loves the Son. The Evangelist frames the whole chapter as the theological summit of the Gospel\'s first arc: Jesus\'s prayer captures in condensed form the entire movement from eternal pre-existence, through the incarnate mission, to the formation of a community that participates in the divine life. What follows — the arrest, trial, and cross — will be the execution of what has here been prayed.</p>'
  },

  "18": {
    "1": '<p>The Kidron Valley (<em>Cheimárrou tou Kedrōn</em> — literally "the winter torrent Kedron") was a seasonal streambed that ran between the eastern wall of Jerusalem and the Mount of Olives. The name derives from a Hebrew root meaning "dark" or "turbid." It carried no water in summer but flooded during the rainy season. David crossed it in flight from Absalom (2 Sam 15:23) — a detail the Evangelist likely intends as a resonant parallel: the rightful king fleeing betrayal. The garden on the other side of the valley was the Mount of Olives garden; Luke and Mark identify it as Gethsemane (Mark 14:32), a name meaning "oil press." The Evangelist does not use the name but supplies the detail that Jesus "often met there with his disciples" — which establishes why Judas knew where to find him.</p>',

    "2": '<p>During Passover week, the city of Jerusalem was packed with pilgrims estimated in the hundreds of thousands. Josephus\'s figures are likely exaggerated, but the logistical reality was that pilgrims who could not find room in the city proper camped on the slopes of the Mount of Olives — within the expanded "Sabbath limit" that still counted as Jerusalem for Passover purposes. The garden was a regular evening retreat, which is why Judas\'s local knowledge made it a viable ambush site. His betrayal did not require infiltrating a secret location — only leading the arrest party to a known meeting place.</p>',

    "3": '<p>The arrest party combines Roman and Jewish elements: "a detachment of soldiers" (<em>speira</em> — a Greek term for the Roman cohort) and "officials from the chief priests and the Pharisees" (Temple police). A full Roman cohort was nominally 600 men, though the term was used loosely for any substantial detachment. The presence of Roman troops alongside Jewish Temple officials indicates official coordination at multiple levels — this was not a mob action but an organized, authorized operation. Fort Antonia, the Roman garrison built by Herod the Great at the northwest corner of the Temple, was the likely source of the Roman soldiers. The torches and lanterns would have been necessary since the Passover full moon, while bright, did not illuminate the shadowed terrain of garden paths.</p>',

    "4": '<p>The Evangelist inserts an editorial note — "knowing all that was going to happen to him" — that is characteristic of the Fourth Gospel\'s presentation of Jesus as the one who acts from superior knowledge rather than being overtaken by events. This stands in deliberate contrast to the Synoptic Gethsemane account, where Jesus\'s anguish and the disciples\' sleeping are prominent features. The Evangelist does not deny that the hour was costly, but he frames Jesus as the one who steps forward to meet it rather than the one who is seized against his will.</p>',

    "5": '<p>The identification "Jesus of Nazareth" (<em>Iēsoun ton Nazōraion</em>) was the standard way to identify Jesus publicly — the patronymic "of Nazareth" distinguished him from the many other men named Jesus (a common name derived from Joshua) in first-century Judea. The Evangelist places particular emphasis on the "I am he" (<em>egō eimi</em>) response, which in the LXX renders the divine self-disclosure of Exodus 3:14 and Isaiah 43:10. Whether or not the soldiers understood the resonance, the Evangelist uses it to signal what is happening at a deeper level: the one who bears the divine name is voluntarily surrendering himself.</p>',

    "6": '<p>The falling back of the soldiers at Jesus\'s response requires historical context. The phrase "I AM" (<em>egō eimi</em>) resonated deeply in a Jewish context: it was the form of the divine name that could not be spoken aloud, that required the priests to pronounce a substitute, that caused crowds to prostrate themselves when heard in liturgical settings. Josephus records that when the divine name was pronounced in a legal context, those present would fall to the ground in awe. Whether the soldiers\' reaction was purely physical surprise, crowd psychology, or a response to genuine spiritual authority, the Evangelist records it as a moment in which the arrest party was overpowered before they had begun — demonstrating that what follows is willed by Jesus, not merely forced upon him.</p>',

    "7": '<p>Jesus\'s repetition of the question — "Who is it you want?" — after the soldiers have already fallen back is a deliberate act of control. He re-initiates the encounter on his own terms. The exchange is not a negotiation but an explicit demonstration of agency: the soldiers are not arresting him; he is presenting himself to them. The Evangelist consistently presents the passion narrative as an active surrender rather than a passive suffering.</p>',

    "8": '<p>Jesus\'s request that the disciples be allowed to go — "If you are looking for me, then let these men go" — is framed in verse 9 as a fulfillment of his earlier prayer ("I have not lost one of those you gave me," echoing 17:12). The disciples\' safety is not incidental: in the Evangelist\'s presentation, the protective prayer of chapter 17 is immediately demonstrated in the narrative of chapter 18. The request is accepted, which underscores that the arrest is structured around Jesus alone — the disciples\' escape is not their cleverness but Jesus\'s provision.</p>',

    "9": '<p>The explanatory aside — "this happened so that the words he had spoken would be fulfilled" — is the Evangelist\'s standard device for connecting events to prior statements. The "words" cited are from Jesus\'s intercessory prayer (17:12), not from Scripture — an unusual move that elevates Jesus\'s own words to the level of texts that history is obligated to fulfill. This is part of the Evangelist\'s sustained presentation of Jesus as the one whose words carry prophetic authority equal to, and in some respects surpassing, the Old Testament.</p>',

    "10": '<p>John alone names both Peter and the servant: Simon Peter and Malchus. The significance of Malchus\'s right ear being cut off is not merely violent confusion. Under Levitical law (Lev 21:17–23), a man with a physical defect or missing limb could not serve in the priesthood; the rule extended by implication to priestly household servants in certain contexts. Malchus served the high priest\'s household. By cutting off his ear, Peter would have rendered him ceremonially unfit for his role — an aggressive act with symbolic weight that the Evangelist, by naming the man, seems to signal. Luke\'s Gospel notes that Jesus healed the ear (Luke 22:51), a detail the Evangelist omits while retaining the names.</p>',

    "11": '<p>The "cup the Father has given me" is the Evangelist\'s only allusion to the Gethsemane prayer, which he has not recorded. In the Hebrew prophets, the "cup" was a potent image for the experience of divine judgment and wrath — the cup God pours out for the nations to drink (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17; Jer 25:15–17; Ezek 23:32–33). Jesus\'s acceptance of the cup is an acceptance of the cup of judgment on behalf of those for whom he has just prayed in chapter 17. The command to Peter to sheath the sword makes the same point as the falling back of the soldiers: violence is not the instrument of this deliverance.</p>',

    "12": '<p>The "commander" (<em>chiliarchos</em>) was a military tribune nominally in command of a thousand men (a <em>chiliarchy</em>) — in practice, the commanding officer of a cohort stationed at Fort Antonia. His presence confirms Roman official authorization for the arrest; this was not a freelance operation by the Temple police alone. Jesus is "bound" (<em>édēsan</em>) — the binding of a prisoner before transport was standard procedure, signaling that he was formally under arrest and would be presented to the relevant authorities for judgment.</p>',

    "13": '<p>The decision to bring Jesus first to Annas before Caiaphas is historically illuminating. Annas (Hanan ben Seth) had served as high priest from approximately AD 6–15, when he was deposed by the Roman governor Valerius Gratus. Under Jewish law, the high priesthood was a lifetime appointment; Roman practice of deposing and replacing high priests was considered irregular by Jewish sensibilities. As a result, Annas retained enormous prestige and informal authority long after his deposition. Five of his sons and his son-in-law Caiaphas held the high priesthood at various points — making his family the dominant priestly dynasty for decades. Bringing Jesus to Annas first was an act of deference to the most powerful figure in the high-priestly network, regardless of formal title.</p>',

    "14": '<p>The reminder of Caiaphas\'s earlier statement — "it is good for one man to die for the people" (11:49–52) — connects the trial narrative directly to the Evangelist\'s earlier presentation of Caiaphas as an unwitting prophet. In chapter 11, the Evangelist had explicitly interpreted that statement as prophecy: Caiaphas said it in his capacity as high priest of that year, and therefore (in the Evangelist\'s reading) his office produced true speech even from his politically motivated calculation. The reader arriving at the arrest scene is meant to carry this earlier frame: what is about to happen is not a miscarriage of justice that undoes the divine plan but a fulfillment of it, even through the corrupt judicial process.</p>',

    "15": '<p>The "other disciple" known to the high priest is widely identified with the Beloved Disciple, generally understood to be John the apostle, the son of Zebedee. A Galilean fisherman having access to the high priest\'s courtyard is historically unusual — it has been explained by later traditions that the Zebedee family supplied fish to the priestly household (Polycrates of Ephesus mentions John\'s priestly connections in a late second-century letter). The Greek word used for "known" (<em>gnōstos</em>) implies a relationship of familiarity rather than casual acquaintance — enough that the doorkeeper would admit a companion on his authority.</p>',

    "16": '<p>The detail of a woman keeping the door of the high priest\'s courtyard is confirmed by Josephus (<em>Antiquities</em> 7.2.1), who notes the practice of women as door-wardens in priestly households. The outer gate of a high-priestly compound would have been guarded; entry required recognition or authorization. The other disciple\'s return to speak to the doorkeeper on Peter\'s behalf is an act of social mediation — using his own access to secure entry for an outsider. This kind of brokered access was ordinary in a world organized around personal relationships and patronage.</p>',

    "17": '<p>The servant girl\'s question — "You aren\'t one of this man\'s disciples too, are you?" — is phrased in Greek with an particle that expects a negative answer, softening what is in effect an accusation. The "too" (<em>kai</em>) implies she has already identified the other disciple as a follower, making Peter\'s situation explicit: he can be honest and risk arrest, or deny and preserve himself. In the honor-shame logic of the culture, a denial of association with a condemned man was a survival strategy, not merely moral cowardice. Peter\'s answer, "I am not," stands in stark contrast to Jesus\'s "I am he" moments throughout the chapter.</p>',

    "18": '<p>The charcoal fire (<em>anthrakia</em>) is a specific word the Evangelist uses only twice in the Gospel — here and in 21:9, where Jesus prepares a charcoal fire on the beach before the restoration conversation with Peter. The verbal echo is not accidental: the Evangelist is establishing a lexical bracket around Peter\'s failure and restoration. The scene at the charcoal fire in the courtyard, where Peter denies Jesus three times, will be answered by the scene at the charcoal fire by the lake, where Jesus asks Peter three times, "Do you love me?" The cold detail of Peter warming himself while Jesus is being interrogated inside captures the social distance Peter has placed between himself and his Lord.</p>',

    "19": '<p>The high priest\'s interrogation focuses on two topics: Jesus\'s disciples and his teaching. This was the standard shape of a preliminary examination (<em>anakrisis</em>) in ancient judicial practice — establishing the nature of the alleged offense before formal charges were framed. The question about disciples implies concern about the scale and organization of Jesus\'s following; the question about teaching implies concern about its content and doctrinal status. Jesus\'s answer redirects both: his teaching was public, his followers are witnesses, there is nothing secret to expose.</p>',

    "20": '<p>"I always taught in synagogues or at the temple, where all the Jews come together. I said nothing in secret." This answer has legal force: Roman judicial procedure and Jewish legal tradition both distinguished between public and secret teaching; clandestine teaching of subversive doctrines was an aggravating factor in conspiracy charges. Jesus\'s claim that his teaching was always public and his audience could be questioned is not merely defensive — it is an appeal to legal procedure. It also stands as a contrast to the secret-society structure that would characterize later Gnostic movements; the Evangelist presents Christianity as emphatically public in its origins.</p>',

    "21": '<p>Jesus\'s counter-demand — "Ask those who heard me" — invokes a basic principle of legal procedure: accusers must present evidence rather than relying on the accused to incriminate himself. Under both Roman and Jewish law, the burden of proof lay with the accusers; the use of coercive interrogation to extract confession was technically irregular, though in practice it was common for persons of lower status. Jesus\'s response is legally astute: he declines to make the prosecution\'s case for them and directs the interrogation toward where the evidence actually exists.</p>',

    "22": '<p>The slap by "one of the officials" was a violation of interrogation protocol: a prisoner had the right to make his case before the court, and striking him during his answer was improper. It was also a powerful social gesture — in a culture where physical dignity and honor were closely linked, striking someone across the face was a calculated dishonoring, not merely physical punishment. Jesus\'s response ("If I said something wrong, testify as to what is wrong; but if I spoke the truth, why did you strike me?") is a legal challenge: either charge him with a specific error or acknowledge that the violence was gratuitous.</p>',

    "23": '<p>Jesus\'s appeal — "testify as to what is wrong" — is framed in legal language: the word <em>martyrēson</em> is the standard term for giving evidence or testimony in a judicial proceeding. He is not refusing to speak but demanding that accusation be based on evidence rather than assumption. The irony the Evangelist is building throughout the trial narrative is that the person being prosecuted is conducting himself with scrupulous legal propriety while those prosecuting him repeatedly violate the procedures they claim to uphold.</p>',

    "24": '<p>Annas\'s decision to send Jesus to Caiaphas without a formal judgment underscores that the interrogation before Annas was preliminary and unofficial — a private examination by the power behind the high-priestly throne. What the Sanhedrin trial under Caiaphas involved is not detailed in the Fourth Gospel (the Synoptics report the night trial and the charge of blasphemy for claiming to be the Son of God). The Evangelist\'s focus throughout the passion narrative is on the Roman trial before Pilate — the politically consequential proceeding that would determine the manner of execution.</p>',

    "25": '<p>The second denial comes while Peter is still standing at the courtyard fire. The question is now posed by an anonymous group — "They asked him" — suggesting a small crowd of bystanders. In the honor culture of the period, Peter\'s situation involves a converging set of pressures: loyalty to his teacher, fear of arrest, and the social pressure of being publicly challenged. His denial in verse 25 echoes the form of his first denial and Jesus\'s "I am he" — the same words, "I am not" (<em>ouk eimi</em>), carrying the weight of the contrast by this point in the narrative.</p>',

    "26": '<p>The third challenge comes from a specific source: a relative of Malchus, whose ear Peter had cut off in the garden. The detail is dramatically precise — Peter\'s act of violence in the garden has followed him into the courtyard and now confronts him through a family member who was directly affected by it. The challenge carries moral weight beyond a simple question of acquaintance: the one asking has personal reason to identify Peter as a dangerous follower of Jesus. Peter\'s third denial triggers the rooster\'s crow, fulfilling Jesus\'s prediction from 13:38.</p>',

    "27": '<p>The rooster\'s crow marked the third watch of the night in Roman reckoning (<em>gallicinium</em>, "cockcrow"), roughly between midnight and 3 a.m. Jewish timekeeping divided the night into three or four watches; the cock\'s crow was a recognized temporal marker widely understood as a transition point in the night. The Evangelist does not record Peter\'s weeping (as the Synoptics do — Matt 26:75; Mark 14:72; Luke 22:62), leaving the moment in silence. The significance will be returned to in chapter 21 at the restoration scene.</p>',

    "28": '<p>The transfer from the Jewish hearing to the Roman governor\'s residence (<em>praitōrion</em> — praetorium) carries a significant irony: the leaders are scrupulously careful not to contract ritual impurity by entering a Gentile house during Passover, so they stay outside — while they are simultaneously engineering an unjust execution inside. Their concern is for ceremonial cleanness, not moral cleanness. The praetorium in Jerusalem has been identified with two possible sites: Herod\'s palace on the western hill of the city, or the Fortress Antonia to the northwest of the Temple mount. Recent archaeological opinion tends toward Herod\'s palace, which was the customary residence of Roman governors when they visited Jerusalem.</p>',

    "29": '<p>Pilate\'s exit to the accusers follows Roman judicial procedure: since they would not enter, he would conduct at least the preliminary stage of proceedings outside. The formal opening question — "What charges are you bringing against this man?" (<em>tina katēgorian</em>) — follows the structure of a Roman <em>cognitio</em>: a formal judicial hearing in which the governor takes direct cognizance of the case. The accusation (<em>katēgoria</em>) had to be stated before proceedings could advance; Pilate is not being pedantic but following required procedure.</p>',

    "30": '<p>The leaders\' response — "If he were not a criminal, we would not have handed him over to you" — is not a legal accusation but a social pressure move: they are appealing to Pilate\'s deference to their judgment rather than presenting a formal charge. The word they use for "criminal" (<em>kakopoios</em> — evildoer) is vague enough to cover anything; it is not a specific charge that Roman law would recognize as actionable. Pilate\'s response in verse 31 calls their bluff: if this is a matter within Jewish jurisdiction, handle it yourselves.</p>',

    "31": '<p>Pilate\'s offer — "Take him and judge him by your own law" — exposes the nature of what the leaders actually want: not just judgment, but execution. Their reply acknowledges this: "We have no right to execute anyone" (<em>ouk exestin hēmin apokteinai oudena</em>). This detail is historically corroborated: the <em>ius gladii</em> (the right of the sword — capital jurisdiction) was reserved for the Roman governor of a province. When Judea became a Roman province in AD 6, the Sanhedrin lost the independent authority to carry out executions. This is also reflected in the Babylonian Talmud (Sanhedrin 7:2): "Forty years before the Temple was destroyed, the Sanhedrin was exiled and did not judge capital cases." Roman control of execution was part of the pacification strategy: it prevented local judicial processes from becoming instruments of revolt.</p>',

    "32": '<p>The Evangelist again uses the fulfillment formula: the reason the leaders sought Roman execution rather than stoning was that Jesus had indicated the kind of death he would die — "lifted up" (3:14; 8:28; 12:32–33), language that pointed to crucifixion, a Roman mode of execution. Jewish execution by stoning (as nearly happened in 8:59; 10:31) would not have fulfilled this prediction. The Evangelist presents the involvement of Rome not as a historical accident but as a theologically necessary element: the specific form of death required the specific jurisdiction.</p>',

    "33": '<p>Pilate\'s private interrogation of Jesus inside the praetorium (from which the Jewish leaders were excluded by their purity concerns) is one of the most historically and theologically significant exchanges in the passion narrative. The opening question — "Are you the King of the Jews?" — frames the charge in political rather than religious terms. The leaders had brought a religious accusation (blasphemy, implicitly); by the time it reached Pilate, it had been translated into the only charge Rome would recognize as capital: sedition, treason, or royal pretension challenging Caesar\'s sovereignty. The question is Pilate\'s attempt to determine whether this prisoner represents a genuine political threat.</p>',

    "34": '<p>Jesus\'s counter-question — "Is that your own idea, or did others talk to you about me?" — is not evasion but a probe of the interrogation\'s basis. If Pilate is asking because he has genuinely observed evidence of royal pretension, the question means one thing; if he is asking because the Jewish leaders have framed the charge, it means another. The distinction matters: a man whose followers call him king without his own political ambitions is not the same threat as one who is actively campaigning for the throne. Jesus is pressing Pilate to identify whose framework is operating.</p>',

    "35": '<p>Pilate\'s answer — "Am I a Jew?" — is dismissive but revealing. He is not personally invested in Jewish messianic categories; his interest is purely pragmatic: what has this man done that warrants Roman legal attention? His words carry the condescension of the Roman administrator who views the internal theological disputes of subject peoples as beneath Roman concern, except insofar as they produce civil disorder. The phrase "your own people and chief priests handed you over to me" locates the initiative precisely: this was not Roman enforcement; it was a Jewish leadership request for Roman execution.</p>',

    "36": '<p>"My kingdom is not of this world" distinguishes Jesus\'s kingship from Zealot-style messianism, which was the form of royal pretension that Rome actually feared. The Zealots and their predecessors had been claiming the kingship of Israel as a basis for armed revolt since the days of Judas the Galilean (AD 6, when Quirinius conducted the census). Pilate would have been alert to any echo of this tradition. Jesus\'s claim is deliberately framed to exclude the military-political dimension: "If it were, my servants would fight." The kingdom he represents does not recruit armies or seize territory by force — it is from "another place" entirely, operating by different means.</p>',

    "37": '<p>Pilate\'s rhetorical question — "You are a king, then!" — is an inference from Jesus\'s use of the word "kingdom." Jesus accepts the label while redefining its content: he was born into the world to "testify to the truth." This is a claim that would resonate differently in Greek philosophical discourse than in Roman political discourse. For a Roman, truth (<em>veritas</em>) was a legal category — the accurate account of facts; for a Greek philosophical audience, truth (<em>alētheia</em>) was the ultimate reality underlying appearances. For the Evangelist, truth is the revelation of God through the Son (14:6; 1:14, 17). Jesus is claiming a kind of kingship that operates through witness and revelation rather than force and territory.</p>',

    "38": '<p>Pilate\'s "What is truth?" has been read across the centuries as cynicism, philosophical despair, and rhetorical dismissal. Lord Bacon read it as jesting; others have seen in it the weariness of a man who had heard too many competing claims in the politically volatile world of first-century Roman administration. The question receives no immediate answer — Pilate goes out before Jesus can respond. The Evangelist\'s irony is acute: the Roman governor asks "What is truth?" and walks away from the one who has just described himself as the witness to truth. Whatever Pilate\'s psychological state, his verdict is immediate: "I find no basis for a charge against him." The judicial finding of innocence will be repeated twice more (19:4, 6).</p>',

    "39": '<p>The Passover amnesty custom — releasing one prisoner at the governor\'s discretion during the festival — is mentioned in all four Gospels (Matt 27:15; Mark 15:6; Luke 23:17 [in some MSS]; John 18:39) but is not attested in other historical sources. It may have been a practice specific to the Judean province, perhaps an accommodation to Jewish sensibilities about the Passover\'s associations with liberation. Pilate\'s offer is both a political maneuver — diffusing the crowd\'s pressure by presenting it as their choice — and a test of whether the demand for Jesus\'s execution reflects genuine popular sentiment or only the pressure of the leadership.</p>',

    "40": '<p>Barabbas (<em>Bar-Abbas</em> — "son of the father") is identified in John simply as a <em>lēstēs</em> — a robber, brigand, or insurrectionist; Luke specifies that he had committed murder in connection with a revolt (Luke 23:19, 25). The same word <em>lēstēs</em> is used by Josephus for the Zealot fighters and their predecessors who carried out resistance operations against Rome, blending banditry and political violence. The crowd\'s choice of Barabbas over Jesus thus has a specific political dimension: they prefer the violent liberator to the one who refuses to fight. The Evangelist ends chapter 18 here, on the threshold of the sentencing; the darkness of the choice is complete without editorial comment.</p>'
  }
}


